Preface. xix

In regard to the List of York Service Books, it may be worth while adding a short account of a unique volume, “Expositio Hymnorum et Sequentiarum,'' published by Wansfort at York, 1507. The volume is in possession of Mr. Kerslake, of Bristol‚

who very kindly placed it in my hands. It is not an exposition of hymns and sequences of the York Use, though doubtless intended to be used in the Diocese, but identical with that accord- ing to the Use of Sarum. The words “Secundum usum Sarum’⁷ have been omitted, and new title-pageS, colophons‚ and intro- ductory letters inserted. The volume does not appear to have been intended in any way for liturgical use, but as a school- book, as will be seen from the introductory letters, which, with the titles and colophons, Ῑ subjoin. I have added part of the Exposition of the Sequence for St. Catharine, which will give a clear idea of the character of the Exposition.

Si quam Ethnicis exhibendis exhibemus diligentiam sanctis quoque literis impartiremus‚ inveniremus profecto cum saepe non minus salis atque leporis in dicendo, tunc ubique sententiarum atque sanctissimae eruditionis longe fertiliorem segetem. Equidem (quod me polliceri possum) fateor cum tota fere doctorum manu nihil Evangeliis esse candidius, facilius, simplicius magisque manifestarium 3 idque non ab re, cum omni creaturae praedicanda norit disertissimus atque idem sanctis- simus interpres: verum qui illis leporem, candorem non fucatum vetus- tate, admirabilem cum summa claritudine brevitatem, pathos saepe huberrimum, gravitatem incomparabilem et artificium ubique summum denegarit, is profecto totus amusus et litteris abhorrens mihi cum primis censebitur. Hoc ea ratione dictum volui, patres juvenesque optimi, quia offendo nonnullos vix trium vocularum satis fidos interpretes, qui sanctas litteras aspernantur tanquam sordidas, negantque pueris subministrandas ; non animadvertentes, immo nescientes decorum quod in illis admissum observatur 3 nescientesque quia in cunctis litteris praestet cultos et sanctos habere animos quam cultioribus ab re Christiana abhorrentes.
